A Peek Into the Future — Results from PCIe Gen 6 SSD Simulations, presented by Young Pak (FADU)

Young Pak introduces trends in NVMe and PCIe-attached SSDs: from SATA-era limits to rapid gains in latency and bandwidth, and asks whether SSDs can keep pace as each PCIe generation raises the bar. One recurring problem is insufficient host compute: roughly one to two hundred thousand IOPS per core is typical, and core counts have not grown enough for dense SSD deployments. Higher NAND layer counts push minimum viable drive capacities upward, so smaller high-performance capacities (e.g. 2–4 TB) become harder while average drive sizes rise; power is capped around 25 W per drive with serious thermal load when dozens of drives fill a 2U front panel, and GPU-heavy servers may push toward liquid cooling—while SSDs unlike GPUs or CPUs must still support hot swap.

Simulation results suggest PCIe Gen 6 SSDs can approach about 6.9 million IOPS at 4 KiB for a single drive, near theoretical link limits, reopening whether that is “enough” or whether architects will look elsewhere. Pak sketches a split in products: “standard” TLC/QLC SSDs at 4 KiB; “nearline” flash aimed at hard-drive–like cost and capacity with larger page sizes (16–32 KiB or more) and relaxed performance, targeting very large capacities (e.g. toward 256 TB class timelines discussed); and NAND positioned more like memory, using SLC-oriented modes with smaller effective access granularities than today’s 4 KiB norm—implying multiple NAND/controller strategies. An exabyte-scale comparison contrasts rack count and power for HDD-based, high-capacity enterprise SSD, and nearline-flash style deployments, motivating nearline for hyperscale storage beside GPU clusters. Closing topics include TCP offload and CPU bypass to NICs, scaling to ~800 Gb/s networking (with cost caveats), larger I/O sizes to reduce DRAM pressure, and ongoing rack power and thermal budgets versus SSD density.
